Rating: 4
I had to make several changes and substitutions, but it still turned out amazing, like restaurant-quality. (Whoever the recipe developer was, was a culinary genius!) These are the changes I made- * Dried sage and Italian parsley for fresh (half the amount of parsley and the whole amount of sage, since dried herbs are more pungent) * Sweet Italian sausages that I made based on this recipe because my supermarket didn't have it on hand: http://www.cooks.com/rec/doc/0,1918,147173-247194,00.html * Added two small sweet tomatoes and 3 sun dried tomatoes * Lamb stew meat * And, because my sauce wasn't reducing fast enough, I also added some mochi (glutinous rice) flour in the form of crushed komachi (little "toasts" traditionally used reconstituted in miso soup). Sounds like a strange fusion, but it turned out so well that I didn't want to go out for dinner the next day; I wanted to stay in!

