Rating: 4
Fantastic! This really tastes like a authentic Tuscan country dish - my wife LOVED it, so I'm definitely going to make it again! I think there are a couple of ways of saving time and making it less complicated for the ordinary kitchen. Firstly, while the reduction with wine is necessary, I don't think the reduction with the porcini juice is - it can all be reduced together after the wine has been reduced. Also, if you buy ground veal/beef and tear the sausage meat into little bits before putting it in, it removes the need for the blender. In my opinion, a dish like this should not be smooth anyway, but if you need to, you can grind it down further by turning down the heat and using a potato masher in the pan. We ate this with a thin spaghetti - which was a total mistake - it should certainly be made with a thick large pasta such as penne for the genuine rustic Tuscan ragu. Superb! (By the way, for those of you that travel to Italy from time to time, you can buy porcini stock/broth cubes in any supermarket which can further intensify the porcini taste in dishes like these).

